      en: 'üî• Main reactions within the country\nMass protests\nIn Kyiv and other major cities (Lviv, Dnipro, Odesa), several thousand people gathered: citizens, students, veterans, and activists took to the streets demanding a veto on the law, which, in their opinion, undermines the independence of anti-corruption bodies.\n\nCirculating slogans and concerns\nProtesters believe that the law subordinates NABU and SAP to the Prosecutor General, who is appointed by the president ‚Äî this means actual control of the authorities over investigations, especially those that might affect Zelensky\'s inner circle.\n\nCivil society anger\nActivists and NGOs (Transparency International Ukraine, Anti-Corruption Center) called the law a "dismantling of independent anti-corruption architecture" and made sharp statements.\n\nüåç International community reaction\nEU and G7 concerned\nRepresentatives of the European Commission, France, and Germany openly warned that the adoption of such a law jeopardized Ukraine\'s European perspective.\n\nInternational human rights organizations\nTransparency International expressed "deep concern," emphasizing that the law destroys reforms initiated after the Maidan.\n\nü§î Why does the law cause negativity?\nUndermines NABU/SAP independence\nGives the prosecutor the ability to suspend or reassign cases, and control bodies lose their independence.\n\nViolates "wartime consensus"\nThe war united society around the government, but this law is perceived as crossing the "line of inviolability."\n\nBlow to the country\'s image\nUkrainians fear that the law may weaken Western trust and lead to the suspension of funding and support.\n\nüß© Government response steps\nZelensky promised to rewrite the law\nThe president stated that within two weeks he would propose a new draft that would restore the independence of the agencies.\n\nConsultations with media and law enforcement\nA round table was held with representatives of security agencies and anti-corruption structures to ease the crisis in society.\n\nüìù Conclusion\nUkrainian society perceived Law No. 12414 as a "rollback" from post-Maidan reforms. Protests demonstrate citizens\' and NGOs\' dissatisfaction: they see the reform as a threat to independence and transparency of power. The international reaction only intensified pressure on Kyiv ‚Äî doubts about the sincerity of the course toward European integration and the fight against corruption became more obvious.',
      
